Everyone says competitive programming is useless for real web development. Then my O(N²) array filter crashed our production servers.

5 min read
Just now

--

Press enter or click to view image in full size

Futuristic city with mathematical overlaysI used to be one of those developers.
You know the type. The one who proudly declares on Twitter, “I’ve been a full-stack engineer for years and I’ve never once needed to invert a binary tree or use a graph algorithm in production!”
I believed that real-world engineering was about knowing how to wire up React components, configure Vercel deployments, and design clean REST APIs. I thought algorithmic complexity was just a hazing ritual invented by Big Tech to make interviews intentionally miserable.
Then, my own code took down our servers during a live event.
And the only thing that saved the project wasn’t a new cloud service or a better framework. It was a dusty, theoretical data structure I had ignored in my computer science lectures.
The Real-Time Disaster
My team was building a real-time coordination platform for a massive venue. Think of it like a live map where users can see the location of their friends and active events in real-time.
We used WebSockets to push location updates to the frontend. The backend was a standard Node.js server.
The core feature was simple: “Find users near me.”
Every time a user moved, they sent their X and Y coordinates to the server. The server would then filter the list of all active users, calculate the distance between them, and return the users within a 50-meter radius.
I wrote the logic exactly how you would write it in a standard web app:
// The "Web Developer" Way: O(N²) Time Complexity
function getNearbyUsers(currentUser, allUsers, radius) {
return allUsers.filter(user => {
if (user.id === currentUser.id) return false; // Calculate Euclidean distance (Pythagorean theorem)
const dx = user.x - currentUser.x;
const dy = user.y - currentUser.y;
const distance = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy);
return distance <= radius;
});
}
During testing with 50 concurrent users, this ran in less than a millisecond. It was perfect. We shipped it.
On launch day, 5,000 people logged into the app simultaneously.
Within exactly two minutes, our WebSocket connections started dropping. The Node.js server stopped responding to health checks. The CPU spiked to 100% and stayed there until the instance completely crashed.
