Cosmic web of glowing connectionsThe Physics of O(N²)
As the servers rebooted, I pulled the logs and realized my catastrophic mistake.
Because we were calculating the distance from every user to every other user on every single movement tick, I had accidentally written an O(N²) algorithm into the hottest path of our application.

• With 50 users, that’s 2,500 distance calculations per tick. The CPU doesn’t even blink.

• With 5,000 users, that is 25,000,000 calculations per tick.
Because Node.js is single-threaded, those 25 million math operations completely blocked the Event Loop. The server literally couldn’t do anything else — it couldn’t accept new connections, it couldn’t ping the database, it couldn’t even breathe. It was mathematically suffocating.
Throwing more servers at this (horizontal scaling) wouldn’t fix the underlying rot. The algorithm itself was poison.
The Algorithm That Saved Us
In a sheer panic, I remembered a concept from a competitive programming problem I had skimmed months ago about collision detection in 2D video games.
In game development, if you check every bullet against every asteroid on the screen to see if they crashed, the game’s framerate dies. Instead, they use a concept called Spatial Hashing (or a Grid Map).
Instead of treating the world as one giant array of users, you divide the map into a mathematical grid.
When a user moves, you don’t update them in a flat list. You use basic division to figure out which “bucket” or “cell” of the grid they are standing in.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Futuristic glowing world map gridWhen it’s time to find nearby users, you don’t check the whole map. You only check the users currently standing in the exact same grid cell as you, plus the 8 adjacent neighboring cells.
I rewrote the core logic in about 20 minutes:
// The "Computer Science" Way: O(1) Time Complexity
class SpatialHash {
constructor(cellSize) {
this.cellSize = cellSize;
this.grid = new Map();
} // Find which grid cell (X, Y) a coordinate belongs to
_hash(x, y) {
const gridX = Math.floor(x / this.cellSize);
const gridY = Math.floor(y / this.cellSize);
return `${gridX},${gridY}`;
}
insert(user) {
const key = this._hash(user.x, user.y);
if (!this.grid.has(key)) this.grid.set(key, new Set());
this.grid.get(key).add(user);
}
getUsersInRadius(x, y) {
const key = this._hash(x, y);
// In production, we also check the 8 neighboring cells
return Array.from(this.grid.get(key) || []);
}
}
We deployed the hotfix.
When the users reconnected, the server didn’t even break a sweat. By bucketing the users, we reduced the number of calculations per user from 5,000 down to roughly 10.
Our time complexity dropped from O(N²) to effectively O(1). CPU utilization plummeted from 100% to a calm, steady 4%.
The Hard Truth About Data Structures
We like to mock competitive programming because the problems often feel disconnected from reality. Nobody is asking you to find the shortest path of a knight on a chessboard in a React codebase.
But here is what I learned the hard way: Data structures are not about memorizing trivia. They are about understanding how to organize information so the physics of the computer can work for you, rather than against you.
You can get away with bad algorithms for years in web development because modern CPUs are ridiculously fast. But scale is a ruthless mirror. The moment you hit real traffic, every inefficient loop, every unnecessary array iteration, and every poorly chosen data structure will be exposed.
I still don’t spend my weekends grinding LeetCode. But I will never, ever mock a computer science fundamental again.
